{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22285"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22285"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.54,0.01,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12955"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43770"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of her diabetes. She was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus five years ago. Her medical history includes hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, and atorvastatin. She works as a personal trainer and reports completing an intense workout yesterday evening. She mentions following a high-protein diet to support her training and has recently increased her protein intake. She also reports mild ankle swelling after standing for long periods and occasional dysuria, though she has no fever or flank pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 27 kg/m\u00b2. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable, though there is trace pedal oedema bilaterally. Her most recent glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) is 52 mmol/mol (6.9%). Her urinary albumin-to-creatinine ratio is 4.5 mg/mmol (normal \u0026lt;3.5), which is elevated compared to her previous result of 2.8 mg/mmol six months ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors may have affected the reliability of the urine result?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High protein intake","Strenuous exercise","Congestive heart failure","Urinary tract infection","Perindopril therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with type 2 diabetes has an elevated urinary albumin-to-creatinine ratio (uACR) compared to her previous result. Several factors can affect the reliability of uACR measurements, making interpretation challenging in certain clinical scenarios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrenuous exercise\u003C/strong\u003E within 24 hours of urine collection can cause transient elevations in urinary albumin excretion. This patient works as a personal trainer and reports completing an intense workout the evening before her test. Exercise-induced albuminuria occurs due to altered renal hemodynamics, increased glomerular permeability, and possibly reduced tubular reabsorption of albumin during and after intense physical activity. This effect is typically temporary and resolves within 24-48 hours after exercise cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause falsely elevated uACR due to increased protein excretion from inflammation in the urinary tract. However, there is no mention of urinary symptoms or signs of infection in this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh protein intake\u003C/strong\u003E can cause physiological albuminuria, particularly after protein-rich meals. While this could potentially affect uACR results, the effect is usually less pronounced than that of strenuous exercise and would be expected to normalise more quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to increased urinary albumin excretion due to altered renal hemodynamics and increased venous pressure. However, this patient shows no clinical signs of heart failure, and it is not mentioned in her medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor) actually tends to reduce urinary albumin excretion rather than increase it. These medications are often prescribed specifically to reduce albuminuria in patients with diabetes and hypertension. Therefore, perindopril would be expected to lower rather than raise the uACR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen assessing albuminuria in patients with diabetes, it\u0027s important to confirm persistent albuminuria with at least two out of three specimens collected over a 3-6 month period. Factors that can cause transient elevations should be excluded before diagnosing diabetic kidney disease. In this case, the most appropriate action would be to advise the patient to avoid strenuous exercise for 24 hours before repeating the uACR test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urinary albumin-to-creatinine ratio can be falsely elevated in certain clinical scenarios including urinary tract infections and congestive heart failure.","Strenuous exercise within 24 hours of testing can transiently increase urinary albumin excretion.","High protein intake can cause physiological albuminuria that does not represent kidney pathology."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Claudel SE, Verma A. Albuminuria in Cardiovascular, Kidney, and Metabolic Disorders: A State-of-the-Art Review. Circulation. 2025 Mar 11;151(10):716-732. doi: 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.124.071079. Epub 2025 Mar 10. PMID: 40063723; PMCID: PMC11902889."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22285"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T20:41:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T20:42:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15250"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr